The deadliest attack against Assyrians since the war began was the [[2010 Baghdad church attack]] which occurred on October 31, 2010. The attack left at least 58 worshipers dead, including 2 priests. More than 100 had been taken hostage by an operation [[al-Qaeda]]-linked Sunni insurgent group the [[Islamic State of Iraq]] claimed responsibility for.

==Statistics==
A 1950 [[CIA]] report on Iraq estimated 98,000 Chaldeans, 30,000 Nestorians (Assyrians), 25,000 Syriac Catholics and 12,000 Jacobites.<ref name=CIA-1950>{{cite web|title=National Intelligence Survey: Iraq: Section 43|publisher=CIA|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/readingroom/docs/DOC_0001252339.pdf|pp=}}</ref> The report used the name Assyrians, in the ethnic sense, for Nestorians, and also noted that Assyrians may be members of the Chaldean and Protestant Churches.<ref name=CIA-1950/>

The Iraqi Minorities Council and the Minority Rights Group International estimated that Iraq's pre-war Assyrian population was 800,000.<ref>{{cite news|last=Jackson |first=Patrick |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/middle_east/6293230.stm#graph |title=Middle East &#124; Crushing Iraq's human mosaic |publisher=BBC News |date=2007-07-13 |accessdate=2012-06-18}}</ref>

According to statistics gathered by the [[Catholic Church]] when doing censuses of Chaldean Catholic diocese in Iraq in 2012 and 2013, [[Chaldean Christians|Chaldo-Assyrians]] in Iraq numbered 230,071 people.<ref name="catholic-hierarchy.org">http://www.catholic-hierarchy.org/rite/dch2.html</ref>

