{{Infobox language |name=Somali Sign Language |altname=SSL |states=[[Somalia]] ([[Somaliland]]), [[Djibouti]] |speakers= ? |ref= |familycolor=sign |fam1=[[Kenyan Sign Language]] |iso3=none |glotto=none }}
'''Somali Sign Language''' ('''SSL''') is a [[sign language]] used by the [[deaf community]] in [[Somalia]] (more specifically [[Somaliland]]) and [[Djibouti]]. It is based on [[Kenyan Sign Language]].
In the 1980s a school for the deaf was established in the Somali Kenyan town of [[Wajir]] by [[Annalena Tonelli]]. Students there became fluent in Kenyan Sign Language. In 1997, three graduates from Wajir helped establish the first school for the deaf in Somalia called the Annalena School for the Deaf named after the late Annalena Tonelli, in [[Borama]]. One of the teachers at Boroma soon founded a school in Djibouti, and, with a bit more difficulty, another was established in [[Hargeisa]].<ref name="Tbagossl">{{cite web |last=Woodford |first=Doreen E. |title=The beginning and growth of a new language: Somali Sign Language |date=2006 |url=http://www.eenet.org.uk/resources/docs/somali_sign_language.php |publisher=Enabling Education Network |accessdate=30 August 2013}}</ref>
